Important note on inheritance:

Using the generic form of the buffers can be quite inefficient and the number
of data copies can be reduced by specializing the buffer class via inheritance.

Suppose we have a structure Foo that is populated from elements of other
structures Bar1 and Bar2:
  Foo.a = Bar1.a;
  Foo.b = Bar2.b;
etc.
and we want to buffer copies of Foo:

To buffer instances of Foo, we need to:
 - create and populate a (temporary) instance of Foo from its constituent pieces.
   This might be done via a non-default constructor, e.g.
   Foo::Foo( const Bar1 & b1,
             const Bar2 & b2)
     :
     a(b1.a),
     b(b2.b)
     ...
  So the code might look like:
     Foo foo(bar1, bar2);
  This results in copying all the contents of Foo once, into the temporary
  instance (foo).

- Call buffer_data with the new instance:
     foo_buffer.buffer_data( foo);
  This results in a second copy of the contents of Foo, this time into the
  buffer.

This data copying can be reduced by overloading the buffer_data(...) method (or
providing a unique method) to circumvent the double copying by passing the
constituent pieces directly.:
  class FooBuffer : public CMLSimpleRingBuffer<Foo>

  void buffer_data (const Bar1 & b1,
                    const Bar2 & b2)
  {
    advance_index();
    Foo & foo = data[buffer_ix];
    foo.a = b1.a;
    foo.b = b2.b;
    ...
  }
Caution/Bonus: This will overwrite the elements of Foo piecemeal. There is no
requirement that all elements get overwritten. This could be desirable, but it
could also be the cause of unexpected data creeping in / being retained
unexpectedly / erroneously.
